</div>

<h2>Privacy & security: where free tools often fall short</h2>
<p>From a privacy perspective, the biggest difference isn’t the tunnel — it’s <em>who runs it</em> and how they make money. Risk points with random free VPNs include:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Overly hungry permissions</strong> on mobile (contacts, SMS, file storage) that a VPN doesn’t need to function.</li>
  <li><strong>Broad “share with partners” clauses</strong> in the privacy policy with no list of who those partners are.</li>
  <li><strong>Outdated ciphers</strong> or support for legacy protocols like PPTP that should be retired.</li>
  <li><strong>No mention of audits</strong> or real-world tests of “no-logs” claims.</li>
</ul>
<p>Paid VPNs can make mistakes too, but the serious players have incentive to publish audits, get called out by security researchers, and fix issues quickly — because that reputation is literally their business.</p>

